    <h1>About me</h1>
    <p>
      In my work life, I am a writer, consultant, former architect, and network tinkerer with longstanding ties to design. I’ve mostly worked in design hubs and through scientific research endowments - including in the cultural and museums world - as a project designer, innovator, communicator or community manager. I build multi-stakeholder projects that help; I support organisations with different scales and mandates to understand each other over complex ideas, regulations and cooperation projects; I am used to taking full responsibility in complex, multi-actor settings, where progress depends less on formal authority than on the ability to build trust, align expectations and keep different perspectives moving in the same direction. 
    </p>
    I came to the conclusion that it’s impossible to build a better world in Europe without mastering our pooled funding mechanisms. So - after almost 13 years of career across engineering, design technology and cultural innovation - I spent the last 4 in Berlin becoming a technically sound go-to person for European cooperation initiatives, acting as an independent EU consultant across sectors and programs, and introducing The strategic access to EU funding* to a multiplicity of EU Funding “newcomer” organisations, from private multi-national academia to small civic society organisations. As my competence in this area had substantially grown over time, last December I could join as a senior consultant the grant office of an Italian R&I foundation whose business model is - since the late 90s - completely built around EU funded projects. This decision allowed me to take a break from my very energy-intensive newcomers and a full-project accountability, and to focus only on a very specific set of complementary horizontal support services for European R&I (Communication, Dissemination and Exploitation). While dramatically increasing the number and the complexity of the initiatives that I can lead, my experience at ICONS Innovation Strategies is helping me to fully acknowledge the tremendous level of competition for public funding across R&I sectors, as well as the needed level of coordination, optimisation and standardization in the EU arena that give organisations chances to achieve “the minimum viable excellence” to truly compete at EU level. Myself only, I lead the contribution to about 30 to 40 large Horizon consortia per year, hence at least 200 million € in funding requests pooled by at least 600 organisations. 

    <p>
      It collects selected project sheets, short reflections, and working notes across public innovation, culture, research, democratic participation, and European funding.
    </p>
  </section>
